  <div class="text">
    <h3>Users</h3>
    <p>
      We’ve identified three main types of people that use Weedmap’s social feature:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        Growers. These are people who might be hobbist or commercial growers of cannabis. They want to share photos their plants and strains to show their skills or to grow their business.
      </li>
      <li>
        Explorers. Some people are new to an area or to the cannabis world and they want to get a better sense of it. Weedmaps Social is one of the best places to go to learn more about where to go, about strains, and to get a feel for this space. Explorers want to answers to questions they pose and to learn more about the cannabis world.
      </li>
      <li>
        Community Leaders. While there is a lot of overlap with growers, Community Leaders want to start conversations with new posts (e.g., photos of their grows, posting photos of products they bought) and they want to help explorers navigate through the waters of the cannabis world.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="pageContent pageText">
  <div class="text">
    <h3>The Problem</h3>
    <p>
      Our Weedmaps Social users are doing the things that are good for the business—discussing strains, products, reviewing listings, etc. The problem is that the product doesn’t make the necessary connections in order to start the growth engine.
    </p>
    <p>
      We decided to start with reviews and social posts. Users write reviews and other users can mark them helpful. It’s a basic function that you see on Yelp, Amazon, and other marketplace products. But Weedmaps doesn’t inform users that they’re review was helpful, which is one of the goals of the action. Same for social posts—there’s no indication that someone liked or commented on your post.
    </p>
    <p>
      What’s also lost in this interaction is the growth of the social graph. When a user finds your review helpful, not only should we tell you that happened, but we also want that user to explore that user’s profile to see their reviews to find those reviews helpful. This creates a virtuous loop that leads to more retention, more helpful reviews and more reviews in general.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="pageContent pageText">
  <div class="text">
    <h3>Solution</h3>
    <p>
      Working with product managers, engineers, moderations, and marketing, we designed a notification loop that aimed to increase retention, increase helpful engagement on reviews, and ultimately lead to more reviews on Weedmaps.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>
